However, it admits that the new standards lay down clearer rules for developers who had previously been limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too Stressed
Singapore is a city state.
Although these new rules could aim to increase the birth rate of the nation, an interview with Singaporeers working in the financial district in the city centre suggests that they will not have a large effect.
"People are still stressed out, homes are expensive, as are education, so many people put it off," a young official says.
"The rest of them have children.
But it is important for me to rely on my own money and time," says another, about 20 years old, young man.
Men and women refer to careers, stress and the cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So whatever the government is trying to force citizens to have children, they're the Singaporeans who have the last word about starting a family.
What is private offline is private and online
Private.
According to a dictionary issued by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something that has a personal character or a "area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any breach".
What is privacy for a person under 16 years of age?
How does it apply this definition in its daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the danger he is exposed to when he publishes on the Internet matters that he certainly would not tell anyone in normal communication?
Reporters from elPeriodico interviewed five boys and girls between 10 and 15 years of age who are frequent internet users.
In four cases they considered the concept of privacy to be "fully self-owned" in a personal context and as "user name and password", if it was a social network.
"I wouldn't disclose my biggest secret," says ten-year-old Jorge in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has accounts for two years.
"It's a very secret secret, my mom can know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"I put nice photos on the FB or pictures of how we play.
I'm also talking to people I know.
I wouldn't share a picture that wasn't mine, or a picture that would make someone laugh," he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on the FB and his nine supporters on Twitter.
Most of them are related.
There's a mother among them who has a name and a password of one of the accounts.
"I set up an account on Twitter to express my views and write interesting contributions.
I don't know if anyone's gonna answer me, I'm just putting them there," she adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far or fast communicating with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept an application from an unknown person.
He wouldn't care if someone recommended someone unknown to him.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks and on the last mentioned network admits that he does not know 20 people on his list of friends.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, neither one of them taught him anything, nor did he want an address or a phone number.
"If they insist on me or require it from me, I simply remove it from my account," he admits.
José applied to Ask after reading his Twitter recommendations.
This boy is not a foreign experience with what is now called cyberbullying.
"A well-known social network friend was blackmailed.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never knew who it was," he confirms.
According to José, the victim didn't report from the account.
"Only one activated a private regime."
Then he explains a series of steps how to set the account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would publish photos known in awkward or awkward situations.
"Of course I would if someone bothered me or just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porrasová, an English teacher and a graduate in the field of Education and Teaching, believes that in order for children and adolescents in social networks to be properly oriented, they must understand that the main objective of these networks is to inform them.
He states: "The internet was created as a tool for finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porrasová notes that academic worker Marc Prensky, graduate of education at Yale University and author of the article Digital Natives and Digital immigrants introduced these concepts to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who need to learn them, and we are only learning ourselves," he says.
It explains that it is a complex topic, "because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at a age when they are not yet ripe for it."
Also, to be, as far as the surroundings are concerned, considerate at a time when what they desire most is to be loved, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," it adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is, asking questions that make them think.
"To tell them not to do anything, it doesn't work," he adds.
Marrielos Porrasová also mentions some of the possibilities: Are there things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why are you doing this on the Internet?
Or: Would you like someone to post your picture the way you published your friend?
Do you know what others are publishing about you?
When you're marking people at the party photos, did you ask these people for permission?
And one more: Do everyone need to know what you're doing all the time?
Another point is to realize that they have to behave in the environment of the Internet as well as outside it.
They're the same rules.
"A person is governed by respect, morality and other principles outside the Internet, and the same should be on social networks," he says.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a first-degree teacher and an education counselor explains that it is necessary for parents of children to read carefully the rules of social networks.
"If they understand each individual indulgence, they have a good basis for them to talk to children about the consequences that they may have on the Internet.
